08410nam a22011655i 9781788922616DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20192019enk    fo  d z      eng d  a2018051178  a97817889226167 a10.21832/97817889226162doi  a(DE-B1597)527569  a(OCoLC)1060178546  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aenkcGB-BST10aP115.4 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aVisualising Multilingual Lives :bMore Than Words /ced. by Paula Kalaja, Sílvia Melo-Pfeifer. 1aBristol ;aBlue Ridge Summit : bMultilingual Matters, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPsychology of Language Learning and Teaching00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAbbreviations -- tContributors -- tForeword -- t1. Introduction -- tPart 1: The Multilingual Self -- t2. Becoming and Being Multilingual in Australia -- t3. Children’s Multimodal Visual Narratives as Possible Sites of Identity Performance -- t4. Integration as Portrayed in Visual Narratives by Young Refugees in Germany -- t5. From the Migration Experience to its Visual Narration in International Mobility -- tPart 2: The Multilingual Learner -- t6. Looking but Not Seeing: The Hazards of a Teacher-researcher Interpreting Self-portraits of Adolescent English Learners -- t7. Looking at Language Through a Camera Lens -- t8. Using Multimodal Analysis to Explore Language Learner Identity Construction -- t9. Multimodal Language Learning Histories: Images Telling Stories -- t10. Study Abroad in Pictures: Photographs as Data in Life-story Research -- tPart 3: Multilingual Teacher Education -- t11. Imagining Second Language Teaching in Brazil: What Stories Do Student Teachers Draw? -- t12. Plurilingual Education and the Identity Development of Pre-service English Language Teachers: An Illustrative Example -- t13. Awareness of Plurilingual Competence in Teacher Education -- t14. ‘The Class of My Dreams’ as Envisioned by Student Teachers of English: What is There to Teach about the Language? -- t15. Conclusion: Lessons Learnt With and Through Visual Narratives of Multilingualism as Lived, and a Research Agenda -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book brings together empirical studies from around the world to help readers gain a better understanding of multilinguals, ranging from small children to elderly people, and their lives. The chapters focus on the multilingual subjects’ identities and the ways in which they are discursively and/or visually constructed, and are split into sections looking specifically at the multilingual self, the multilingual learner and multilingual teacher education. The studies draw on rich visual data, which is analysed for content and/or form and often complemented with other types of data, to investigate how multilinguals make sense of their use and knowledge of more than one language in their specific context. The topic of multilingualism is addressed as subjectively experienced and the book unites the current multilingual, narrative and visual turns in Applied Language Studies. It will be of interest to students and researchers working in the areas of language learning and teaching, teacher education and bi/multilingualism, as well as to those interested in using visual methods and narratives as a means of academic research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMultilingualismxPsychological aspects. 0aMultilingualism-Psychological aspects. 0aSecond language acquisitionxPsychological aspects. 0aSecond language acquisition-Psychological aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aVisual narratives.  aapplied language studies.  amultilingual learner.  amultilingual self.  am